  <sections xmi:id="_XFovAKZVEeCmzNtTCfivQw" name="Select methods for the correctness of functional performance of safety mechanisms" guid="_XFovAKZVEeCmzNtTCfivQw">
    <sectionDescription>&lt;p>&#xD;
    To ensure the correct functional&amp;nbsp;performance of the safety mechanism, taking into account timing and accuracy the&#xD;
    test methods detailed in the table below, taken from ISO 26262, volume 4, clause 8.4.2.3.2 shall be applied according&#xD;
    the ASIL of the item under development.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    &amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&#xD;
    Correctness of functional performance of safety mechanisms&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;table dir=&quot;ltr&quot; border=&quot;1&quot; cellspacing=&quot;1&quot; cellpadding=&quot;2&quot; width=&quot;656&quot;>&#xD;
    &lt;tbody>&#xD;
        &lt;tr>&#xD;
            &lt;td bgcolor=&quot;#CCCCCC&quot; valign=&quot;center&quot; rowspan=&quot;2&quot; width=&quot;70%&quot; colspan=&quot;2&quot;>&#xD;
                &lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot; align=&quot;center&quot;>&#xD;
                    &lt;b>Methods&lt;/b>&#xD;
                &lt;/p>&#xD;
            &lt;/td>&#xD;
            &lt;td bgcolor=&quot;#CCCCCC&quot; valign=&quot;top&quot; width=&quot;30%&quot; colspan=&quot;4&quot;>&#xD;
                &lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot; align=&quot;center&quot;>&#xD;
                    &lt;b>ASIL&lt;/b>&#xD;
                &lt;/p>&#xD;
            &lt;/td>&#xD;
        &lt;/tr>&#xD;
        &lt;tr>&#xD;
            &lt;td bgcolor=&quot;#CCCCCC&quot; valign=&quot;top&quot; width=&quot;8%&quot;>&#xD;
                &lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot; align=&quot;center&quot;>&#xD;
                    &lt;b>A&lt;/b>&#xD;
                &lt;/p>&#xD;
            &lt;/td>&#xD;
            &lt;td bgcolor=&quot;#CCCCCC&quot; valign=&quot;top&quot; width=&quot;7%&quot;>&#xD;
                &lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot; align=&quot;center&quot;>&#xD;
                    &lt;b>B&lt;/b>&#xD;
                &lt;/p>&#xD;
            &lt;/td>&#xD;
            &lt;td bgcolor=&quot;#CCCCCC&quot; valign=&quot;top&quot; width=&quot;7%&quot;>&#xD;
                &lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot; align=&quot;center&quot;>&#xD;
                    &lt;b>C&lt;/b>&#xD;
                &lt;/p>&#xD;
            &lt;/td>&#xD;
            &lt;td bgcolor=&quot;#CCCCCC&quot; valign=&quot;top&quot; width=&quot;8%&quot;>&#xD;
                &lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot; align=&quot;center&quot;>&#xD;
                    &lt;b>D&lt;/b>&#xD;
                &lt;/p>&#xD;
            &lt;/td>&#xD;
        &lt;/tr>&#xD;
        &lt;tr>&#xD;
            &lt;td valign=&quot;top&quot; width=&quot;6%&quot;>&#xD;
                &lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot; align=&quot;center&quot;>&#xD;
                    1a&#xD;
                &lt;/p>&#xD;
            &lt;/td>&#xD;
            &lt;td valign=&quot;top&quot; width=&quot;64%&quot;>&#xD;
                &lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot; align=&quot;left&quot;>&#xD;
                    Back-to-back test (a)&#xD;
                &lt;/p>&#xD;
            &lt;/td>&#xD;
            &lt;td valign=&quot;top&quot; width=&quot;8%&quot;>&#xD;
                &lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot; align=&quot;center&quot;>&#xD;
                    +&#xD;
                &lt;/p>&#xD;
            &lt;/td>&#xD;
            &lt;td valign=&quot;top&quot; width=&quot;7%&quot;>&#xD;
                &lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot; align=&quot;center&quot;>&#xD;
                    +&#xD;
                &lt;/p>&#xD;
            &lt;/td>&#xD;
            &lt;td valign=&quot;top&quot; width=&quot;7%&quot;>&#xD;
                &lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot; align=&quot;center&quot;>&#xD;
                    ++&#xD;
                &lt;/p>&#xD;
            &lt;/td>&#xD;
            &lt;td valign=&quot;top&quot; width=&quot;8%&quot;>&#xD;
                &lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot; align=&quot;center&quot;>&#xD;
                    ++&#xD;
                &lt;/p>&#xD;
            &lt;/td>&#xD;
        &lt;/tr>&#xD;
        &lt;tr>&#xD;
            &lt;td valign=&quot;top&quot; width=&quot;6%&quot;>&#xD;
                &lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot; align=&quot;center&quot;>&#xD;
                    1b&#xD;
                &lt;/p>&#xD;
            &lt;/td>&#xD;
            &lt;td valign=&quot;top&quot; width=&quot;64%&quot;>&#xD;
                &lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot; align=&quot;left&quot;>&#xD;
                    Performance test (b)&#xD;
                &lt;/p>&#xD;
            &lt;/td>&#xD;
            &lt;td valign=&quot;top&quot; width=&quot;8%&quot;>&#xD;
                &lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot; align=&quot;center&quot;>&#xD;
                    +&#xD;
                &lt;/p>&#xD;
            &lt;/td>&#xD;
            &lt;td valign=&quot;top&quot; width=&quot;7%&quot;>&#xD;
                &lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot; align=&quot;center&quot;>&#xD;
                    ++&#xD;
                &lt;/p>&#xD;
            &lt;/td>&#xD;
            &lt;td valign=&quot;top&quot; width=&quot;7%&quot;>&#xD;
                &lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot; align=&quot;center&quot;>&#xD;
                    ++&#xD;
                &lt;/p>&#xD;
            &lt;/td>&#xD;
            &lt;td valign=&quot;top&quot; width=&quot;8%&quot;>&#xD;
                &lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot; align=&quot;center&quot;>&#xD;
                    ++&#xD;
                &lt;/p>&#xD;
            &lt;/td>&#xD;
        &lt;/tr>&#xD;
        &lt;tr>&#xD;
            &lt;td valign=&quot;top&quot; colspan=&quot;6&quot;>&#xD;
                &lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot; align=&quot;justify&quot;>&#xD;
                    a A back-to-back test compares the responses of the test object with the responses of a simulation&#xD;
                    model to the same stimuli, to detect differences between the behavior of the model and its&#xD;
                    implementation.&#xD;
                &lt;/p>&#xD;
                &lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot; align=&quot;justify&quot;>&#xD;
                    bA performance test can verify the performance concerning e.g. task scheme, timing, power output in the&#xD;
                    context of the whole test object, and can verify the ability of the hardware to run with the intended&#xD;
                    control software.&#xD;
                &lt;/p>&#xD;
            &lt;/td>&#xD;
        &lt;/tr>&#xD;
    &lt;/tbody>&#xD;
&lt;/table>&#xD;
&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot; align=&quot;left&quot;>&#xD;
    &lt;strong>&lt;em>Copyright ISO 2011. All rights reserved. Reproduced with permission of ANSI. This is a draft ISO Standard&#xD;
    that is subject to change without notice and cannot be referred to or relied upon as a final ISO&#xD;
    standard.&lt;/em>&lt;/strong>&#xD;
&lt;/p>&lt;br /></sectionDescription>
  </sections>
  <sections xmi:id="_dUZXUKZVEeCmzNtTCfivQw" name="Select methods for the consistency and correctness of implementation of external and internal interfaces" guid="_dUZXUKZVEeCmzNtTCfivQw">
    <sectionDescription>&lt;p>&#xD;
    To ensure the consistency&amp;nbsp;and correctness of the implementation of the internal and external interfaces, please&#xD;
    refer to &quot;Table&amp;nbsp;5-Consistency and correctness of implementation of external and internal interfaces&quot; located&#xD;
    at&amp;nbsp; ISO 26262, volume 4, clause 8.4.2.3.3. This table covers:-&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;blockquote style=&quot;MARGIN-RIGHT: 0px&quot; dir=&quot;ltr&quot;>&#xD;
    &lt;p>&#xD;
        Test of external interfaces&#xD;
    &lt;/p>&#xD;
    &lt;p>&#xD;
        Test of internal interfaces&#xD;
    &lt;/p>&#xD;
    &lt;p>&#xD;
        Interface consistency test&#xD;
    &lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;/blockquote>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    All these tests are recommended for ASIL A and highly recommended for ASILs B,C or D.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    Interfaces tests of the test object include tests of analog and digital inputs and outputs, boundary tests and&#xD;
    equivalent-class tests to completely test the specified interfaces, compatibility, timings and other specified ratings&#xD;
    for the test object.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    Internal interfaces of an ECU are tested by static tests for the compatibility of software and hardware as well as&#xD;
    dynamic tests of SPI- or I&lt;sup>2&lt;/sup>C-communications or any other interface between elements of an ECU.&#xD;
&lt;/p></sectionDescription>
  </sections>
  <sections xmi:id="_miVGgKZVEeCmzNtTCfivQw" name="Select methods for the effectiveness of diagnostic coverage of hardware fault detection mechanisms" guid="_miVGgKZVEeCmzNtTCfivQw">
    <sectionDescription>&lt;p>&#xD;
    To ensure the effectiveness of the diagnostic coverage of the hardware fault detection, please refer to &quot;Table&#xD;
    7-&amp;nbsp;Effectiveness of diagnostic coverage of hardware fault detection mechanisms&quot; located at ISO 26262, volume 4,&#xD;
    clause 8.4.2.3.3. this table covers&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;blockquote style=&quot;MARGIN-RIGHT: 0px&quot; dir=&quot;ltr&quot;>&#xD;
    &lt;p>&#xD;
        Fault injection tests&#xD;
    &lt;/p>&#xD;
    &lt;p>&#xD;
        Error Guessing&#xD;
    &lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;/blockquote>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    Both techniques are recommended for ASILs A or B and highly recommended for ASILs C or D&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    Fault injection introduces faults into the model at runtime to determine how the software reacts. This is normally&#xD;
    achieved through a special test interface or hardware. This technique is often employed to improve test coverage of the&#xD;
    safety requirements, this is because during normal operation safety mechanisms are not involved.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    Error guessing employs expert knowledge and data collected from experience or the field. This is used to anticipate&#xD;
    possible errors in the test object.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot; align=&quot;justify&quot;>&#xD;
    For references to fault models see ISO 26262 volume 5: , Annex D, Table D.1&#xD;
&lt;/p>&lt;br /></sectionDescription>
  </sections>
  <sections xmi:id="_zXYtYKZVEeCmzNtTCfivQw" name="Select methods for the  level of robustness" guid="_zXYtYKZVEeCmzNtTCfivQw">
    <sectionDescription>&lt;p>&#xD;
    The types of tests to ensure the level of robustness of the elements being tested are the following:&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;blockquote style=&quot;MARGIN-RIGHT: 0px&quot; dir=&quot;ltr&quot;>&#xD;
    &lt;p>&#xD;
        Resource usage tests&#xD;
    &lt;/p>&#xD;
    &lt;p>&#xD;
        Stress tests&#xD;
    &lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;/blockquote>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    Both types of tests are recommended for ASILs A or B and highly recommended for ASILs C or D&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    Resource usage tests can be done statically or dynamically, for instance&amp;nbsp;by checking code size, analyzing the&#xD;
    interrupt usage in the code&amp;nbsp;or monitoring the code dynamically at run time&amp;nbsp;This helps to verify that the&#xD;
    worst case scenarios do not run out of resources.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    Stress tests are used to verify the correct operation of the item under high operational loads or extreme environmental&#xD;
    conditions.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    Please refer to &quot;Table 8-Level of robustness&quot;, located in ISO 26262, volume 4, clause 8.4.2.3.5&#xD;
&lt;/p></sectionDescription>
  </sections>
  <purpose>&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot; align=&quot;left&quot;>&#xD;
    To describe the verification tools, methods and environment with pass and fail criteria to be applied at the HW-SW&#xD;
    integration level.&#xD;
&lt;/p></purpose>
</org.eclipse.epf.uma:TaskDescription>
